ies. Bebop’s complexity and radicality, Leal contends, made it possible for those like Araki, Salinas, and Wing who grappled daily with state-sanctioned violence to challenge a racially supremacist, imperial nation, all while hearing and making the world anew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBop (Music)xHistory and criticism. 0aJazzxHistory and criticismzJapan. 0aJazzxHistory and criticism. 0aJazzxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aMusic and racexHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024583?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024583/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles